"1220":"1220","about 1220":"about 1220","1150":"1150","1270":"1270","1182":"1182","1119":"1119","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Corby, Northamptonshire, England":"Corby, Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom","Scampston, Yorkshire, England":"Scampston, Yorkshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Latimer","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: occupational name for a Latinist, a clerk who wrote documents in Latin, from Anglo-Norman French <i>latinier</i>, <i>latim(m)ier</i>. Latin was more or less the universal language of official documents in the Middle Ages, displaced only gradually by the vernacular – in England, by Anglo-Norman French at first, and eventually by English."],"variants":[{"name":"Latner","meanings":["English: occupational name for a worker in or maker of latten or brass, from Middle English <i>latoun</i> ‘brass’ (Old French <i>laton</i>). This name may sometimes have been confused with   Latimer  .","Altered form of German   Lattner   or   Lettner  ."]},{"name":"Lattimore","meanings":["English: variant of   Latimer  ."]},{"name":"Latimore","meanings":["English: variant of   Latimer  ."]},{"name":"Lattimer","meanings":["English: variant of   Latimer  ."]},{"name":"Lattner","meanings":["English: variant of   Latimer  .","German: occupational name for a carpenter who prepared or used laths or slats, from Middle High German <i>latte</i> ‘slat, lath’ + <i>-n</i> (plural suffix) + the agent suffix <i>-er</i>."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William I Latimer was born in 1200, his father, Geoffrey De Latimer, was 75 and his mother, Si, was 81. He had at least 1 son with Mayla Lane. He died in 1270, in Corby, Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 70."},"et":{"1200–1270":"1200–1270","1150–Male":"1150–Surnud","1182–1287":"1182–1287","1220–1268":"1220–1268","1125–Male":"1125–Surnud","1119–Female":"1119–Surnud","1125":"1125","1268":"1268","1200":"1200","22 November 1268":"22. november 1268","1287":"1287","1220":"1220","about 1220":"umbes 1220","1150":"1150","1270":"1270","1182":"1182","1119":"1119","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Corby, Northamptonshire, England":"Corby, Northamptonshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Scampston, Yorkshire, England":"Scampston, Yorkshire, England"},"fi":{"1200–1270":"1200–1270","1150–Male":"1150–Kuollut","1182–1287":"1182–1287","1220–1268":"1220–1268","1125–Male":"1125–Kuollut","1119–Female":"1119–Kuollut","1125":"1125","1268":"1268","1200":"1200","22 November 1268":"22. marraskuuta 1268","1287":"1287","1220":"1220","about 1220":"noin 1220","1150":"1150","1270":"1270","1182":"1182","1119":"1119","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Corby, Northamptonshire, England":"Corby, Northamptonshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Scampston, Yorkshire, England":"Scampston, Yorkshire, England"},"fr":{"1200–1270":"1200–1270","1150–Male":"1150–Décédé","1182–1287":"1182–1287","1220–1268":"1220–1268","1125–Male":"1125–Décédé","1119–Female":"1119–Décédée","1125":"1125","1268":"1268","1200":"1200","22 November 1268":"22 novembre 1268","1287":"1287","1220":"1220","about 1220":"environ 1220","1150":"1150","1270":"1270","1182":